docs.abstract: Steven Mnuchin, whose apparently offhand remark on the dollar caused a tumble, joins many Treasury secretaries whose words have been given more meaning than intended.
docs.snippet: Steven Mnuchin, whose apparently offhand remark on the dollar caused a tumble, joins many Treasury secretaries whose words have been given more meaning than intended.
docs.lead_paragraph: DAVOS, Switzerland — His name now appears on the dollar bill. But that does not mean it is safe for him to actually talk about the dollar.

headline.main: For Mnuchin, a Lesson in How Words Can Move Markets
headline.print_headline: Loose Talk Trips Markets, Mnuchin Finds

docs.abstract: The $11.6 billion deal for Bioverativ would bolster the French pharmaceutical giant’s portfolio as it faces falling sales for its diabetes drug, Lantus.
docs.snippet: The $11.6 billion deal for Bioverativ would bolster the French pharmaceutical giant’s portfolio as it faces falling sales for its diabetes drug, Lantus.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — The French drug maker Sanofi said on Monday that it had agreed to acquire Bioverativ, a biopharmaceutical company focused on treatments for hemophilia and other rare blood disorders, for $11.6 billion in cash.

headline.main: Sanofi, Facing Threat From Generics, Moves to Buy Hemophilia Drug Maker

docs.abstract: The arrival of voice-controlled assistants in cars raises security and privacy concerns. Depending on automakers’ setups, it could expose your information or property.
docs.snippet: The arrival of voice-controlled assistants in cars raises security and privacy concerns. Depending on automakers’ setups, it could expose your information or property.
docs.lead_paragraph: Amazon’s Alexa voice-controlled virtual assistant is the Chatty Cathy of the tech world, a digital darling that consumers can’t get enough of. It can tell chicken jokes, order pizza and turn off the kitchen faucet. So it’s not surprising that Alexa has made the leap from the home to the car.

headline.main: Alexa, What Happened to My Car?
headline.print_headline: Alexa, What Happened to My Car?

docs.abstract: Major tech companies took steps to prevent foreign meddling online before voters in Ireland cast ballots on Friday. Here’s how those efforts are working out.
docs.snippet: Major tech companies took steps to prevent foreign meddling online before voters in Ireland cast ballots on Friday. Here’s how those efforts are working out.
docs.lead_paragraph: DUBLIN — Craig Dwyer recently sat in an office above a convenience store in downtown Dublin, scrolling through a database he had compiled of hundreds of online ads that have popped up about Ireland’s abortion referendum on Friday.

headline.main: Ireland’s Abortion Referendum Becomes a Test for Facebook and Google

docs.abstract: It’s an uncertainty that has huge economic consequences.
docs.snippet: It’s an uncertainty that has huge economic consequences.
docs.lead_paragraph: Here are two things most economists can agree upon: They want an economy where everyone who seeks a job can get one. Yet for the economy to be dynamic, some people will always be unemployed, at least temporarily as they move between jobs.

headline.main: How Low Can Unemployment Really Go? Economists Have No Idea
headline.print_headline: How Low Can Unemployment Go? No One Knows

docs.abstract: The social network is ending Explore, an experiment in countries like Bolivia and Cambodia, where it had separated news and other publishers from its main site.
docs.snippet: The social network is ending Explore, an experiment in countries like Bolivia and Cambodia, where it had separated news and other publishers from its main site.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Facebook said on Thursday that it would end an experiment in six countries that separated posts from news sites and publishers from other material on the social network.

headline.main: Facebook to End News Feed Experiment in 6 Countries That Magnified Fake News
headline.print_headline: Facebook Experiment Ends as Fake News Rises
